    <exercise>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What observations can you make about the graph of <m>y = h(x)</m> based on the graphs of <m>y = f(x)</m> and <m>y = g(x)</m>? Explain why your observations make sense.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the shape of the product graph? Why is the product graph shaped this way?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What type of function arises from multiplying two linear functions together?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <task xml:id="exer-prod-zero">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In order for a product of two numbers to be zero, what do you know about one or both of the numbers you are multiplying together?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A function arising from the product of two lines has an <m>x</m>-intercept at <m>x = 3</m>. The equation is written as a product of two linear functions. What do you know about one of the linear functions? How does this information relate to <xref ref="exer-prod-zero"/>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Through investigating the product of two lines, we are able to find an equation of a function from the equations of the lines that are multiplied together to form it.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find an equation for each of the products of the pairs of lines in <xref ref="exer-tbl-plot-prods"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How are the <m>x</m>-intercepts of each line related to the <m>x</m>-intercepts of the product graph?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How are the <m>x</m>-intercepts of each function related to its equation?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>
  </worksheet>

  <worksheet xml:id="act-mult-lines-desmos">
    <title>Multiplying Lines Electronically With Desmos</title>
    
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Now that you have graphed the product of two lines by hand, explore the product of two lines using Desmos as you complete the student page, <xref text="title" ref="act-mult-lines-desmos"/>. Do you get the same results? What more do you notice?
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Set up Desmos to play with products of linear functions, as follows:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Type <m>y = x - p</m> into the first input line. Click on the <m>p</m> button to create a slider for <m>p</m>. Start the slider at <m>p = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Type <m>y = x - q</m> into the first input line. Click on the <m>q</m> button to create a slider for <m>q</m>. Start the slider at <m>p = 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Type <m>y = (x - p)(x - q)</m> into the third input line.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Type <m>y = x^2</m> into the fourth input line.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Play with the <m>p</m> slider.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How does the graph of the product of two lines change as you change <m>p</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Why does the change in <m>p</m> cause the product graph to appear as it does?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What happens to the product graph with <m>p</m> is less than 0? Why does that make sense?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            From your previous mathematical experiences, what is the graph of the product called?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Play with the <m>q</m> slider until you can explain what is happening to the product graph and why it is happening. We call the graph to the product of two lines a parabola. A parabola is the graph of the quadratic function.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Edit the first input line to be <m>y = a (x - p)</m>. Create a slider for <m>a</m>. Edit the third input line to be <m>y = a (x - p)(x - q)</m>. Play with the <m>a</m> slider.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      
      <task xml:id="exer-parab-changea">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For what values of <m>a</m> does the parabola appear to be wider than <m>y = x^2</m>? Why do you think <m>a</m> has this effect on the parabola?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <xref ref="exer-parab-changea"/>, is the parabola wider than <m>y = x^2</m>? Why or why not? Argue from the equations, not the appearance of the graphs.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For what values of <m>a</m> does the parabola appear to be steeper than <m>y = x^2</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain what <m>a</m> does to the parabola.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Turn off <m>y = x^2</m> (click on the colored button to the left of the equation). Reset the <m>a</m> slider so that <m>a = 1</m>. Play with the sliders for <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>. Compare the lines to the parabola. What do the lines and teh parabola always have in common no matter how you change <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Continute to play with all three sliders, <m>a</m>, <m>p</m>, and <m>q</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Try each of these three possibilities:
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Both lines have positive slopes.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Both lines have negative slopes. (What additional change do you need to make?)
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              One line has a positive slope and the other line has a negative slope.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How can you tell from the lines what a parabola created from the product of the lines will open upward? Reason from the equations of the lines and the parabola.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How can you tell from the lines what a parabola created from the product of the lines will open downward? Reason from the equations of the lines and the parabola.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How can you tell from the lines where the parabola will intersect the <m>x</m>-axis?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How can you tell from the lines where the parabola will intersect the <m>y</m>-axis?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is a line of symmetry?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            How can you find the line of symmetry for a function that is the product of two lines? Why does this make sense?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Each parabola has a highest or lowest point, called the vertex. What information about the vertex can you determine from the lines? Explain.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>

  </worksheet>

  <activity xml:id="act-polygraph">
    <title>Polygraph for Parabolas</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        Now that we have learned something about how quadratic functions arise in context and their connection to linear functions, let's spend some time describing them. You teacher will provide a Class Code for the Desmos activity, <pubtitle>Polygraph: Parabolas</pubtitle> in the Quadratic Bundle on Teacher Desmos. You will be randomly paired with another classmate. Polygraph is a variation of the commercial game, <pubtitle>Guess Who?</pubtitle>. Play 2 rounds of the game or as directed by your teacher.
      </p>
      <p>
        When time is called, your teacher will provide you another Class Code, this time for the Desmos activity, <pubtitle>Polygraph: Parabolas, Part 2</pubtitle>. Complete the activity, taking notes on vocabulary that will help you describe and discuss quadratic functions and their graphs more efficiently.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </activity>

